The lead–acid battery is a battery technology with a long history. Typically, the lead–acid battery consists of lead dioxide (PbO2), metallic lead (Pb), and sulfuric acid solution (H2SO4) as the negative electrode, positive electrode, and electrolyte, respectively (Fig. 3) [31]. The lead–acid battery requires a container that is usually made of thermoplastics (e.g., acrylonitrile–butadiene–styrene, styrene–acrylonitrile resin, polycarbonate, polyvinyl chloride, polyolefin) [32]. The operation of lead–acid secondary battery is based on Eq. (1) [33].Fig. 3
Schematic of lead–acid batteries.
