Ni–Cd battery is another mature technology with a long history of more than 100 years. In general, Ni–Cd battery is composed of a nickel hydroxide positive electrode, a cadmium hydroxide negative electrode, an alkaline electrolyte, and a separator. An Ni–Cd battery is usually assembled with a plastic or metal case that contains a sealing plate equipped with a self-sealing safety valve. The plastic containers for Ni–Cd battery are made from polypropylene, polystyrene, and flame-retarded plastics, which are preferable to the metal-based counterpart and have relatively high corrosion resistance, low weight, and ease of visual control of the electrolyte level [32]. The charge and discharge operation mechanism of Ni–Cd batteries can be presented as the following Eq. (2):22NiOOH+2H2O+Cd⇔2NiOH2+CdOH2E0=1.29V\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$2{\text{NiOOH}} + 2{\text{H}}_{2} {\text{O}} + {\text{Cd}} \Leftrightarrow 2{\text{Ni}}\left( {\text{OH}} \right)_{2} + {\text{Cd}}\left( {\text{OH}} \right)_{2} \quad E^{0} = 1.29\,{\text{V}}$$\end{document}

Ni–MH batteries were first studied in the 1960s and have been on the market for over 20 years as portable and traction batteries [32]. Ni–MH batteries comprise metal hydride anodes (e.g., AB5-type [LaCePrNdNiCoMnAl], A2B7-type [LaCePrNdMgNiCoMnAlZr], or AB2-type [VTiZrNiCrCoMnAlSn] metal hydride active materials), nickel hydroxide cathodes, and alkaline electrolytes (e.g., KOH, KOH/LiOH, KOH/NaOH/LiOH). A separator is usually utilized as the insulator between anodes and cathodes, functions as the medium for absorbing electrolytes, and is composed of synthetic nonwoven material. The battery chemistry of Ni–MH batteries is shown in Fig. 4 and described by the following Eq. (3):Fig. 4
Schematic of Ni–MH batteries.
